    <prp:abstract>The role of dust in shaping the spectral energy distributions of low mass 
galaxies remains poorly understood. Recent results from the Herschel Space 
Observatory imply that dwarf galaxies contain large amounts of cool (T~20K) 
dust, coupled with very modest optical extinctions. 

These seemingly contradictory conclusions may be resolved if dwarfs harbor a 
variety of dust and star geometries. For instance, if the dust in dwarfs is 
located at larger galactocentric radii than for more massive galaxies or 
quiescent dark clumps, this may explain the observations.

We propose ALMA observations of one true-occulting dwarf galaxy already observed
with the Hubble Space Telescope. Combined the ALMA/HST observations will map
both the dust attenuation and emission on the finest scales practical in the whole 
foreground galaxy. These attributes dust structures in a low-mass disk can then
be used to break the dichonomy seen in stacked SEDs; is the disk simply more 
extended, or very clumpy and cold? The small scale structure observed by both 
ALMA and HST can then be used to probe the role of turbulence in this ISM through
the spatial power spectrum.</prp:abstract>
